histological development and progression of glomerulonephritis observed in 
untreated animals. Although no definite explanation is available at present to 
explain how MZR caused decreased anti-DNA antibody production and delay in the 
development of glomerulonephritis in these animals, it is suggested that it acts 
by directly suppressing the hyperfunctioning B cells of lupus mice. MZR may 
prove to be a promising immunosuppressant for the treatment of human lupus, in 
view of its lesser side effects such as bone marrow suppression or 
hepatotoxicity.

